description.text:
This is a cat friendly door closing system for doors that are inside the house. The system is designed to be as smooth and un-intrusive as possible: You barely notice its there, but the doors will never stay open again.

I'm using this on 4 doors in my house now, for a couple of weeks. Its working excellent, and its saving a lot of heating costs.

This is inspired by the design of Lippifuss. This is a simpeler design, but its using two 608 bearings for extra smoothness.

What you need:

  • Two 608ZZ bearings, preferably closed ones. (I used https://www.123-3d.nl/123-3D-Kogellager-608ZZ-DME00003-i20-t13131.html)
  • Two printed sets of pulleys ( lid + pulley + axis stl files)
  • One ballast tube. (either use ballast.stl or use white 16 mm electric wiring tube)
  • Fish wire or rope.
  • Screws
  • Lead for your ballast tube (I used http://www.ballast-producten.nl/producten/ballast-lood/loodhagel/) You can also use sand, but you might need a bigger tube.
  • Clean and lube your hinges. Disable the door handle.
  • Cats (optional)

The axis should press-fit in the 608 bearing, which should press-fit in the pulley. (you probably need to push a bit hard) The lid is optional and just to make it look nicer.

Cat pulling a door open: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=exf7rj-6tU0

Cat pushing a door open: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=edDsoldNQ64

Fully open: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uGhsFahRczU

description.text:
Update: Well, a 15mm MAXLE is one thing but when the RockShox needed service and I swapped on a spare Fox fork, I went from the bolt-in MAXLE to the quick release Fox axle - and due to the larger diameter, it pushed against the plastic bin I'd mounted the holder, and with cold weather, wound up popping off. This is a redesign which will help address both of those issues - it's now compatible with quick release thru-axles as well as having the ability to drill a hole and mount an M5 bolt, such as those you'd find on a water bottle cage or the T25 torx bolts used to attach a brake disc rotor.

My bike has a 15mm thru-axle that has to come out whenever I put the bike in the car. Originally I'd put the axle back in the fork, but then I'd need to pull it again to put the wheel in. Then I started just leaving it on the floor, but it would get dirty and could roll around. To solve the problem, I created this simple little thing which I attached to a bin (holding spare shoes/helmets/clothes/etc) in the back of the car using double-sided tape. It is a loose fit so the axle snaps in easily, but it holds it well enough that it doesn't fall out. When I take it out of the bike, I pop it into the holder, and it stays there until I'm ready to put the wheel back in.

If you're curious about the 6mm hex wrench that I use with the axle, it's held in place with a magnet salvaged from a hard drive that's taped to the inside of the bin. The gaffer's tape on the hex wrench keep it from going in too far so it won't hit the fork when I turn it.

title: SRAM 12t X-Sync pulley for 1x drivetrains
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
There are a ton of jockey pulleys here on Thingiverse, but most of them are the older 11t design. I recently managed to smash up two SRAM jockey pulleys (no idea how, the derailleur was fine) and I found out that replacement pulleys were $30 - I decided it was time for me to add to the growing collecting of Thingiverse jockey pulleys.

For some reason, SRAM thinks that jockey pulleys need the narrow/wide design that is so wonderful for chain retention on chainrings. Don't know as it really helps anything all that much, but hey, whatever, I matched up what they had and duplicated it as best as I could.

I have the raw model included, as well as a split model which can be printed in halves and then superglued together. I've found supports on the whole model to be annoying to clean up, so the split halves and superglue winds up being easier.

This version is designed around the 626 bearing that SRAM uses in the X-Sync pulleys, and includes two press pieces so you can press out the old ones and press them into the printed replacement. (Reuse the SRAM end caps) However, it seems that the 626 bearing is less common, so I'm going to try creating a version using the more common 688 bearing. That won't work natively with the SRAM hardware, though, so this version should still be useful.

description.text: Clip on gutter, hang lights.

Updates - 1/01/2018
Added landing gear to protect battery and eventually camera from hard landings. If you strap the batteries to the top of the drone this won't be as much of a problem. The landing gear consists of four 3" long 3/16" bolts (apologies for the imperial units, I wanted to use M5 but this was all I could find). Attached to the base of these bolts is a front spring, back spring and two side springs. They are designed to absorb some shock if the drone lands at an angle, and will prevent too much torque from being applied to the arms. These springs will break easily, but they only take 20 minutes to print, and prevent other more important things form breaking

Added some vents below the motor mounts to prevent overheating. This is very important! Without these vents the motors will quickly break.

Thickened some areas on the body which were breaking to easily.

Listed below are all the parts I used. I'm pretty new to quadcopters, but it seems like most of the mounts used for flight controllers, PDB's, ESC's, motors etc. are pretty standard, so if you want to use different parts they should still work fine.

  • 4x Racerstar Racing Edition 2205 BR2205 2300KV 2-4S Brushless Motor
  • Racerstar RS20Ax4 20A 4 in 1 Blheli_S Opto ESC 2-4S
  • F3 Flight Controller Acro 6 DOF
  • Matek Systems PDB-XT60 W/ BEC 5V & 12V 2oz Copper
  • FlySky FS-i6 2.4G 6CH AFHDS RC Transmitter With FS-iA6B Receiver
  • 4x 5 inch propellers
  • 31x M3 bolts (most of these cam with the parts listed above)
  • 15x M3 nuts

The arms of this quad were printed in ABS and the body was printed in PLA. Everything was printed with 100% infill. Some time in the future I'll be adding a camera mount.
Duct a 40mm fan onto a 30mm part or vise-versa. Made to fit onto an e3d hotend fan mount.
Print with 100% in-fill in ABS

description.text:
Check out my YouTube channel https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC82xXciVxsQKthONKeYbhnw for how to videos about 3d modeling, printing and home automation

Update: I've started a series of how-to videos for this project, please check out the full playlist, including Hardware (https://youtu.be/WNp4G49tkrQ), Software (https://youtu.be/7dm9OPTRvUQ) and openHAB configuration (https://youtu.be/Lnv-2xBhabo) here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLH-d6dcsARGNHlRyqTrwyiWJLNb1YpbPS

More info about the breakout board I designed and used in this project: https://youtu.be/cJbiTxJr2iA

This is a bit of a remix of my other design (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2539897), without an OLED screen and more compact (not as tall).

I designed this unit to house my NodeMCU carrier board (https://goo.gl/U2fY7y) with as little clearance as possible.The function for this unit is to act as an LED Strip controller, connected to my home automation system (openHAB) via MQTT.

The Arduino code is basically my fork of bruhautomation's excellent ESP LED controller code (https://github.com/bkpsu/ESP-MQTT-JSON-Digital-LEDs), with some specific modifications and fixes I made for my application (including speed/color control tweaks, fixing the flicker that was present in the original code when using my WS2812 strips, adding some of my own effects, and creating a group MQTT topic to control multiple strips with one command).

The sample openHAB configuration files can be found here: https://community.openhab.org/t/nodemcu-mqtt-led-strip-controller-build-config-how-to-videos/39902

So far, I've been using these as my Kitchen cabinet lights, but for 2017 season holiday decorations, rather than fight with strings of lights outside, I decided to take the "easy" way out and line all my windows and doors with these. I have a total of 10 controllers/strips, all synchronized (FX, power, animation speed) via MQTT, and automated from openHAB (different effects based on day of the week). I think it looks great and I may just keep these in all year, for regular accent lighting.

I'm using these WS2812 strips (http://amzn.to/2ilIvdf) because they're good quality, pretty cheap, and get here in 2 days with Prime (they appear to be combined from smaller lengths of strips, but that makes no difference to me. For the NodeMCU, check these links out -
NodeMCU ESP8266 dev board v0.9 ($6 & Prime from Amazon: http://amzn.to/2hd6RJk, $3 from AliExpress: https://goo.gl/fQGwBN) or 1.0 (http://amzn.to/2ymAkak).

Check out my (mostly functional) 3D designs - (https://www.thingiverse.com/bkpsu/designs) ! If you like them and want to support my projects, use one of the links below when you're planning to buy anything from these sites (it won't cost you anything extra!). Thank you in advance!

How to build controller
Parts List (Affiliate links to parts I've used/tested):
-this enclosure
-5 meter 5V WS2812 LED Strip (http://amzn.to/2ilIvdf) (comes with 3-wire male connector you need to connect to the controller)
-NodeMCU breakout board (https://goo.gl/U2fY7y)
-NodeMCU ESP8266 dev board v0.9 ($6 & Prime from Amazon: http://amzn.to/2hd6RJk, $3 from AliExpress: https://goo.gl/fQGwBN) or 1.0 (http://amzn.to/2ymAkak).
-headers (http://amzn.to/2fNe81C)
-solid hook-up wire, 22awg (http://amzn.to/2xbTaAW)

(Optional):
-5V 10A power supply (use for longer lengths of strip, ~2M or greater) (http://amzn.to/2BXcrE9)
-Aluminum Channel (for mounting outside, and helps diffuse the single LEDs into a smoother light) (http://amzn.to/2l2UH77)
-DC connectors (male/female), for easy and modular setup (http://amzn.to/2iQNmmO)

Initial build

Print enclosure and cover
Solder left/right inner headers onto the OSHPark carrier board (15 pins each)
Stick NodeMCU board onto carrier board, USB connector facing down when looking at the silk-screen text on the carrier board
Solder 3-pin male LED connector onto carrier board as follows and wrap connector around the headers and down the middle (between the headers and underneath the NodeMCU):

Board Wire Color OLED
5v Red VCC
Gnd White Gnd
D4 Green Din

(Your LED Strip connections/wire colors might be different)

Final Assembly:

Put NodeMCU carrier board in, ensuring it fits snugly (USB connector is visible)
Put enclosure cover on, and secure with small screws (or glue in place)
Connect the extra red/white (5VDC/Gnd) wires to your 5V power supply (either via a connector plug or directly to the power supply)
Program controller. I'm using the code here: https://github.com/bruhautomation/ESP-MQTT-JSON-Digital-LEDs with a few minor mods:

Line 0 (before any comment text) add:

"#define FASTLED_INTERRUPT_RETRY_COUNT 0" (this prevents flicker I've noticed with my strips)

Line "#define NUM_LEDS 54" <- change the number to your # of LEDs

Line "#define DATA_PIN 5" <- change this to 5 (D4 output on NodeMCU)

Line "#define CHIPSET WS2811" <- change to WS2812 or the type of LED you're using

Line "#define COLOR_ORDER GRB" <- change order of colors to match your strip (i.e. if you set a red color, but get a green instead and vice versa, just change "GRB" to "RGB")

After this, you will need to either incorporate the controller into your home automation system. I use openHAB (www.openhab.org), but this will work with any system that can send JSON commands to MQTT topics (or can be reprogrammed to use any other method of setting the effect, brightness or speed. Check out bruhAutomation's readme (located at the GitHub link above) for other examples.

If you do use openHAB, I've posted sample items/sitemap/rules configuration files here: https://community.openhab.org/t/nodemcu-mqtt-led-strip-controller-build-config-how-to-videos/39902

description.text:
This is my Fully 3d printed accessory arm, I call it that because adding any model to the accessory clip and printing it makes that thing compatible with the arm. So far i have only made a holder for my Galaxy s7 but i hope to add more items to it soon.

Assembly should be easy enough to figure out but if not ask anything you need to in the comments :) You probably want to screw down the base somewhere, thats all the hardware you will need really.

printing out more of the arm 2 and the arm pins makes for a bigger arm than the two sections shown but it gets less stable the more arms you add, i should probably add solid arms later then you can pick your own infill.

These three examples were done using the lowest resolution available; higher resolutions produce details which the printer cannot reproduce. Small succulents with thick leaves were chosen. All are presented at full size. They are: Haworthia_attenuata.stl
Echeveria_hybrid.stl
Euphorbia_lactea_cristata.stl Images comparing the models to the actual plants are shown at the lower left.
All the files can be printed with or without rafts.  The smallest plant, Haworthia attenuata, prints quickly but can be scaled up to more clearly show the ribbing of the leaves.

description.text:
EDIT 2017-12-15: added a slightly larger holder for the 1080p Microsoft Lifecam Studio. Tested to fit the camera well.

A simple camera holder for the Microsoft Lifecam Cinema. I found that the tiny screw holding on the standard mount was way too weak to keep the camera secure, so I remixed this from the camera mount I used on my old Wanhao i3.

The camera is held in nice and securely with a captive M4 nut and bolt. If you use a nyloc nut this thing shouldn't come loose ever!

The height of the camera is designed such that you can see what is happening at the nozzle. The exact positioning of the camera can be fine tuned;

  • it can be rotated quite a bit and it's still spaced out enough such that it won't hit the Y axis clamp.
  • the height should be OK 'as is', but you can add washers and spacers between the mount and its holder to raise it.

Printer:

HyperCube Evolution

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Bill of Materials

2 x M5x10 bolts
1 x 3030 extrusion T-nut
1 x Camera Holder Base (printed)
1 x Lifecam Camera Holder (printed)
1 x M4 nut (nyloc is best if you plan on repositioning the camera a lot)
1 x M4 bolt, between 25 and 35mm length (dependent on number of spacers)
washers or spacers to get desired height

Assembly Steps
  1. Fit the M4 nut into the camera holder. Depending on your printer tolerances, this may be a very tight fit: if this is the case, screw a long bolt into the nut, place it where it needs to be pressed in, and lightly tap it in with a small hammer or mallet.
  2. Place the M4 bolt into the holder, thread washers/spacers (if any) for desired height, then thread into the camera holder in the hole at the bottom.
  3. Remove the factory standard mount from the Lifecam and slide it into the holder. If the camera is too loose, put one or two pieces of tape on the inside the mount to sturdy it up.
  4. Affix the assembled unit onto the underside of the middle Y axis extrusion beam.
  5. Fine tune positioning as desired.

description.text:
I wanted to print flexible filament but could not find anything on thingiverse that did not require ordering a new bearing or even fit correctly.

I decided to create my own. This is the first try and it works! It also adds 1mm more preload on the spring to make it grip tighter.

I have ran MakerFlex through it just fine, I do not have anything stretchy (like ninja flex) to try it on those materials.

Please leave your comments on how it works for you.

Folger Tech FT-5

Rafts:

Supports:

To install, dissasemble the extruder and replace the backplate with this one. The extruder goes back together exactly the same way. I did loosen the heat break and push it up against the bottom of the new back plate. It made loading easier and eliminated the gap. You will have to readjust your Z height if you do this.

Tips: You may want to smooth the inside of the filament hole in the base to make feeding easier. When loading filament, do not press the lever down more than you need to as this will make the filament miss the lower hole.

It can be a bit fiddly getting the filament to load but once you get it in, it works fine.

description.text: This is a very simple epoxy mixing cup, fast and cheap to print. There are two parts: the cup and the divider. The cup is printed in vase mode (one continuous vertical layer), you can print it at the fastest setting of your printer (0.35mm or 0.4mm). The divider should be printed at 0.2mm. Insert the divider to create the desired epoxy mixing ratio: I made this for the XTC-3D 3D Print Coating epoxy, which mixes at 2:1, so I bend the divider at the middle crease to 120 degrees; for 1:1 mixes just use the straight divider. Pour the epoxy components, make sure levels are equal on both sides (easier if the filament is transparent). Fold the divider completely at the middle crease, fold it again at the other two creases, and use it as a mixing stick. This is a one-use thing, so use your cheapest filament :)

remixed_from.title: Spool holder using M8 rod and 608ZZ bearing v2

description.text:
A simple spool holder using a tried and tested design, using 8mm rod and 608 roller bearings (the kind you find in skateboards, rollerskates, etc.)

The SCAD file for making a spool clamp to your exact specifications is in the remix source. I have created two spool clamps that fit most filament spools such as eSun and Aurarum (the filament brands I use).

Bill of Materials

Printed
1 x Rod Holder
2 x Spool Clamps

Hardware / Not Printed
1 x 8mm threaded rod - approx 140mm (slimline clamp) or 160mm (standard clamp)
2 x 608 bearings (I got mine from an old skateboard in a thrift shop for $1)
4 x 8mm washers
2 x 8mm nuts
1 x 8mm wing nut

Assembly Steps
  1. Thread a nut and a washer onto the rod, slide it into the printed mount (flush side) so that almost all the thread sticks out from the side with the recess
  2. Thread a washer and a nut onto the rod, from the recessed side. Do it up hand tight, then use two spanners to tighten the two nuts solidly together.
  3. Press fit the 608 bearings into the two spool clamps.
  4. Thread a washer onto the rod, then a spool clamp.
  5. This is where you would put your filament spool
  6. Thread a spool clamp onto the rod, then a washer, then the wing nut. Do up the wing nut.

Your filament is now secure. To remove the filament, do steps 4-6 backwards.

Small experiment with the Vase mode/Spiralize.

Print info:

  • UM3
  • Blue CPE filament
  • Layer height 0.2

The original STL was designed for testing purposes, it is much bigger than needed for use as a Christmas tree decoration, printed scaled to 40-50% looked good.

To hang it on the Christmas tree you will need to attach a wire loop on top.

I slightly modified Rocholl's original Kossel design for FlSun's 2020 extrusions and to use M4 hammerhead nuts, instead of the M4 square nuts.

This 20 USD/EUR/GBP upgrade (filament and hammerhead nuts) makes a big difference in putting together a square delta frame. Downside is, of couse, that you need access to a working printer.

description.text:
This is the first public version of my Trinus print head using an E3Dv6 (Bowden) with integrated Precision Piezo Z probe.

The design (style) has been based on the Ormerod E3D Precision piezo by Dignitate but due to the strange layout and offset of the Trinus print head. I started this design from scratch.

There are four parts to the design

  • Back plate - designed to sit in the standard Trinus metal plate
  • Hotend and Universal PCB mount - two separate pieces
    Hotend mount - the E3Dv6 universal heatsink slides into the slot beneath the piezo dome
    Universal PCB mount - this slides into the same slot as the universal heatsink and provides a solid 360 degree support for the heatsink. The PCB mount is held in place by two M3 screws
  • 27mm piezo mount - to support the piezo disc when sandwiched between the back plate and hotend mount

I used M3 button head hardware and I have tapped all the holes in the Hotend mount with M3 threads. I also put a strip of double sided tape in the PCB tray to prevent the PCB from becoming dislodged.

06/12/17 Uploaded 20mm piezo mount - note that this is untested as I only have 27mm piezo elements.

This is an updated version of the original vacuum former I designed a few years ago, unfortunately I don't have my printer anymore so I won't be able to test it but it should print well with a couple pieces needing some support material. They have a nice large base you can mount along with the hose routed out of the way.

There is two class sizes a 200mm and a 150mm made to fit within printers that size, the usable space is 154mm and 104mm respectively.

There is 5 pieces one of which will be printed twice.

  • Main 150mm or 200mm (The main piece to be printed
  • Clamp_Piece 150mm or 200mm (These clamp around the plastic and will need to be
    printed twice)
  • Slots 150mm or 200mm (This is a plate for the object to sit on and is 154mm or 104mm)
  • Angled_Pipe (This piece connects to the main piece underneath, the inner diameter is 27mm if you need to make an adapter)
  • Universal_Adapter (This connects to the Angled_Pipe and should accommodate hoses from 27-40mm)

The slot piece sits in the main piece. Two clamp pieces are using together with a piece of plastic between. Then the angled_pipe is glued to the main piece and the universal adapter is glued to the angled pipe. I'd recommend using something like pvc cement to connect the pieces together.

I've also included .stp files in the .zip file to for easier editing.

description.text: This is a model of a Turk's head knot. ( http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turk's_head_knot ) It is a 3-lead, 5-bight knot (3x5), with a triple strand. In the first file, I added a small base to the bottom to help with printing. Without the base, the 5 initial contact points tended to detach and the overhang on the bottom is pretty extreme. The example was printed on a printrbot (thanks Mike!) from white ABS. It measures approximately 50mm in diameter at its widest point. The knot path was generated via a Sketchup ruby script I wrote, and then the strand cross-section was extruded along that path. This created some very complex objects and took some work to figure out how to deal with overlapping areas and get a manifold object. I have generated other lead/bight combinations, but this was one of the nicer-looking early attempts. Edit: I added the Turk's Head .stl without the base, for those that would like to add support material, or try and print it without a base.

  • 4 x Schraube DIN 912 M5 x 12
  • 9 x Schraube DIN 912 M3 x 25
  • 4 x Mutter DIN934 M5
  • 9 x Mutter DIN934 M3

Die Abstandhalter sind für die M3 Schrauben und werden zwischen Frontplatte und Platine montiert, damit die Frontplatte sich beim Verschrauben nicht nach innen drücken kann.

title: Dehydrator Spool Passive Bearing Wide and Narrow versions

description.text:
Allows you to use a standard inexpensive food dehydrator for your filament. I have gone through 100s of rolls of filament with this setup, you do not need bearings for something like this. Bearings actually are NOT desirable because the spool will start unraveling itself as the filament falls off the roll when it is held sideways. The friction caused by the side of the filament spool sliding over the PETG/PLA plastic is actually a necessary part of such a setup.

Uses a few 3mm screws and washers to hold it in to the dehydrator base. There are many different models of dehyrator on Amazon that will work for this.

I made the large plastic divider that the filament PTFE feed tube mounts to out of PC from Home Depot - get the 1/8" size and cut into a strip the right width and then bend and bolt it together with some M3 screws. If you drill the PTFE tube hole just the right size it will press in and stay there, at least mine has.

The larger size has an OD of 39mm and works with Solutech, Esun, MG chemicals filament + many others with a large diameter hole.

The smaller size is for Taulman 3D filament spools and may work with other small ID spools, it has a OD of 18mm.

I print mine in PETG but PLA should work, just may warp a little more over time.

Very cool idea (not mine it was posted as a competition idea by Everythingmechanical http://blog.makezine.com/archive/2010/04/makerbot_giveaway.html) Seemed easy enough to make a simple one so here it is. 2 part inner tube 2 part outer tube and a tumbler (you need 5 to complete assembly) I've included the SKP file for those interested. I'm still very new to 3d modeling and sketchup (learned a lot this past couple of weeks tho) so my images are still pretty ordinary. If I get the chance I'll come back and do an exploded image to show assembly a little bit more clearly. I assumed that glue could be used to attach the end caps to the inner and outer tubes but it would not take much to put in a small hold and use a screw (allowing the tumblers to be changed if wanted ( or taken apart of the combination is forgotten) obvious improvements would be to alter the tumbler design so the actual value for each tumbler could be changed, etc. I can see a few ways this might be done but none I'm terribly happy with right now. UPDATE:
Plate 5 v1.1
This is a modified tumbler with many pick groves to make it harder to use machine tolerance issues to determine the combination. Plate 5 v1.2
This is a modified tumbler in 2 parts enabling the tumbler to be "re-configured" to change the values.

This design has not been tested.
Print out 1 each of plates 1 to 4 and 5 of place 5.
Plates 1 and 2 assemble to make the inner tube (see the image supplied)
Plates 3 and 5 assemble to make the outer tube but only glue the end cap in place after the tumblers (plate 5) have been put in place (and tested with the inner tube.
Mark the faces of the tumblers as desired.
